[{"id":30760,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are correct","Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect","Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\mathrm{BaCl}_2, \\mathrm{NaCl}$ are soluble but on adding $\\mathrm{HCl}(\\mathrm{g})$ to $\\mathrm{BaCl}_2, \\mathrm{NaCl}$ solutions, Sodium or Barium chlorides may precipitate out, as a consequence of the law of mass action.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30796,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>15</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Bi</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;will get dissociated as:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Bi</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#8652;</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>Bi</mi><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math></p><p>Here,</p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi>sp</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>108</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>5</mn></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi>sp</mi></msub><mn>108</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mfrac bevelled=\"true\"><mn>1</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>08</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>73</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mn>108</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mfrac bevelled=\"true\"><mn>1</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>15</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mol</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30749,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["\\(3.6 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{M}~ \\mathrm{AB}_2, 5.0 \\times 10^{-4} \\mathrm{M}~ \\mathrm{XY}\\)","\\(2.0 \\times 10^{-4} \\mathrm{M}~ \\mathrm{AB}_2, 0.8 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{M}~ \\mathrm{XY}\\)","\\(2.0 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{M}~ \\mathrm{AB}_2, 2.0 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{M}~ \\mathrm{XY}\\)","\\(1.5 \\times 10^{-4} \\mathrm{M}~ \\mathrm{AB}_2, 1.5 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{M}~ \\mathrm{XY}\\)"],"answer":2,"solution":"When equal volumes are mixed molarity reduce to half.<br />For precipitation \\(\\mathrm{Q}_{\\mathrm{SP}}=\\left[\\mathrm{A}^{+2}\\right]\\left[\\mathrm{Y}^{-}\\right]^2  \\gt  \\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{SP}}\\)<br />(1) \\(\\mathrm{Q}_{\\mathrm{SP}}=\\left(1.8 \\times 10^{-3}\\right)\\left(\\frac{5}{2} \\times 10^{-4}\\right)^2  \\lt \\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sP}}\\)<br />(2) \\(\\mathrm{Q}_{\\mathrm{SP}}=\\left(10^{-4}\\right)\\left(0.4 \\times 10^{-3}\\right)^2 \\lt \\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}\\)<br />(3) \\(\\mathrm{Q}_{\\mathrm{SP}}=\\left(10^{-2}\\right)\\left(10^{-2}\\right)^2  \\gt  \\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sP}}\\)<br />(4) \\(\\mathrm{Q}_{\\mathrm{SP}}=\\left(\\frac{1.5}{2} \\times 10^{-4}\\right)\\left(\\frac{1.5}{2} \\times 10^{-3}\\right)^2 \\lt \\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sP}}\\)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (2 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30858,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$1.0 \\times 10^{-9}$","$1.0 \\times 10^{-10}$","$1.0 \\times 10^{-5}$","$1.0 \\times 10^{-11}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"Let solubility of $\\mathrm{AgCl}=x \\mathrm{~mole} / \\mathrm{L}$\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{AgCl} \\rightleftharpoons \\mathrm{Ag}^{+}+\\mathrm{Cl}^{-} \\\\\n& \\text {i.e., } K_{\\mathrm{sp}(\\mathrm{AgCl})}=x \\times x \\\\\n& \\mathrm{KCl} \\longrightarrow \\mathrm{K}^{+}+\\mathrm{Cl}^{-} \\\\\n& {\\left[\\mathrm{Cl}^{-}\\right] \\text {from } \\mathrm{KCl}=0.1 \\mathrm{~m}} \\\\\n& \\text { Total }\\left[\\mathrm{Cl}{ }^{-}\\right] \\text {in solution }=x+0.1 \\\\\n& K_{s p}(\\mathrm{AgCl})=\\left[\\mathrm{Ag}^{+}\\right]\\left[\\mathrm{Cl}^{-}\\right]=x(x+0.1) \\\\\n& 1.0 \\times 10^{-10}=x(x+0.1) \\\\\n& 1.0 \\times 10^{-10}=x^2+0.1 x \\\\\n& 1.0 \\times 10^{-10}=0.1 x \\quad\\left(\\text { as } x^2< < 1\\right) \\\\\n& x=1.0 \\times 10^{-9} \\mathrm{~mol} / \\mathrm{L}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (07 May Online)","image":null},{"id":30849,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{pH}=4.70$","$\\mathrm{pH} < 4.70$","$\\mathrm{pH}$ of solution will be equal to $\\mathrm{pH}$ of acetic acid","$4.76 < \\mathrm{pH} < 5.0$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned}\n\\mathrm{pH} & =\\mathrm{pK}_a+\\log \\frac{[\\text { salt }]}{[\\text { acid }]} \\\\\n& =4.76+\\log \\frac{\\frac{7.5}{500}}{\\frac{5}{500}}=4.7+\\log 1.5=4.87\n\\end{aligned}$\nHence correct answer is $4.76 < \\mathrm{pH} < 5.0$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (25 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30802,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e0f8d61f-0114-425c-ad16-2d896566f217-image.png\" style=\"width: 570px; height: 147px;\" /></p><p>At <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>298</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math> : in aq. solution <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mrow></mfenced><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>14</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>14</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30837,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$1.798 \\mathrm{~L}$","$0.36 \\mathrm{~L}$","$17.95 \\mathrm{~L}$","$0.18 \\mathrm{~L}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\left(\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}\\right)_{\\mathrm{PbCl}_2}=3.2 \\times 10^{-8}=32 \\times 10^{-9}$\n$\\mathrm{PbCl}_2 \\rightleftharpoons\\underset{\\mathrm{s}}{\\mathrm{Pb}^{2+}}+\\underset{2 \\mathrm{s}}{2 \\mathrm{Cl}^{-}}$\n$\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}=\\left[\\mathrm{Pb}^{2+}\\right]\\left[\\mathrm{Cl}^{-}\\right]^2$\n$\\mathrm{~K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}=4 \\mathrm{s}^3=32 \\times 10^{-9}$\n$\\mathrm{~s}^3=8 \\times 10^{-9}$\n$\\mathrm{~s}=2 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{M}$\n$\\frac{\\mathrm{w}}{\\mathrm{M} . \\mathrm{W}.} \\times \\frac{1}{\\mathrm{~V}_{\\mathrm{L}}}=2 \\times 10^{-3}$\n$\\frac{0.1}{278} \\times \\frac{1}{\\mathrm{~V}_{\\mathrm{L}}}=2 \\times 10^{-3}$\n$\\mathrm{~V}_{\\mathrm{L}}=\\frac{0.1 \\times 1000}{278 \\times 2}=0.18 \\mathrm{~L}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 1 Online)","image":null},{"id":30875,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{s}=\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}}{128}\\right)^{1 / 4}$","$\\mathrm{s}=\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}}{256}\\right)^{1 / 5}$","$\\mathrm{S}=\\left(256 \\mathrm{~K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}\\right)^{1 / 5}$","$\\mathrm{s}=\\left(128 \\mathrm{~K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}\\right)^{1 / 4}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\mathrm{Ksp}=108 s^5$\n$1 \\times 4^4 \\times s^{1+4}=256 s^5=\\mathrm{Ksp}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":30861,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["9","10","11","8"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\mathrm{Mg}^{2+}+2 \\mathrm{OH}^{-} \\rightleftharpoons \\mathrm{Mg}(\\mathrm{OH})_2$\n$\\mathrm{~K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}=\\left[\\mathrm{Mg}^{2+}\\right]\\left[\\mathrm{OH}^{-}\\right]^2$\n$\\left[\\mathrm{OH}^{-}\\right]=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}}{\\left[\\mathrm{Mg}^{2+}\\right]}}=10^{-4}$\n$\\therefore \\mathrm{p}^{\\mathrm{OH}}=4$ and $\\mathrm{p}^{\\mathrm{H}}=10$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":30831,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<math><mn>8</mn><mo>x</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn></mrow></msup><mi>M</mi></math>","<math><mn>8</mn><mo>x</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>11</mn></mrow></msup><mi>M</mi></math>","<math><mn>8</mn><mo>x</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup><mi>M</mi></math>","<math><mn>8</mn><mo>x</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup><mi>M</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>(i) <img height=\"105\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c7f733f2-0bef-402d-85e4-ed69aea4f2ee-image.png\" width=\"280\" /><br /><br />(ii)&nbsp;<img height=\"88\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/302ea6b1-41a1-4ccc-aa0d-ea2b3da1c7bd-image.png\" width=\"330\" /><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mi>K</mi> <mrow> <mi>s</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow> </msub> <mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup> <mrow> <mn>10</mn></mrow> <mrow> <mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow> </msup> <mo>=</mo><msup> <mrow> <mrow><mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mn>2</mn><msup> <mi>S</mi> <mo>&#8242;</mo> </msup> <mo>+</mo><mn>0.1</mn></mrow> <mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow> <mn>2</mn> </msup> <msup> <mi>S</mi> <mo>&#8242;</mo> </msup> </mrow> </math><br /><br />or <math> <mrow> <msup> <mi>S</mi> <mo>&#8242;</mo> </msup> <mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup> <mrow> <mn>10</mn></mrow> <mrow> <mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow> </msup> <mi>M</mi></mrow> </math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30811,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Since <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>PO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math> is salt of weak acid <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>PO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and weak base <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pH</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mi>pka</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>pkb</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>23</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>75</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>24</mn><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>7</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30824,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></msub><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>9.8</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>98</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>40</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>40</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>50</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>20</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>50</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pOH</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>log</mi><mn>4</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mi>pH</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn></math></p><p><br />&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (07 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30841,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CCl</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CCl</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;have vacant <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mo>-</mo></math>orbital and incomplete octet. So they accept lone pair&nbsp;and act as Lewis acids.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30792,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>HCl</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>KCl</mi></math>","Deionised water","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>AgNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Due to the common ion effect of chloride, the solubility of silver chloride is less in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCl</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KCl</mi></math>, compared to solubility in water.&nbsp;In deionized water no common ion effect will take place so maximum solubility</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>AgCl</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#8652;</mo><msup><mi>Ag</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>(</mo><mi>aq</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>(</mo><mi>aq</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30786,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d68775c0-e657-452d-9e0e-0ede56e860c9-image.png\" style=\"width: 156px; height: 130px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a8c34015-f8a3-41f5-ae52-eb28da50276b-image.png\" style=\"width: 157px; height: 130px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4cc47cdf-71fc-46f8-b281-2767d90b450f-image.png\" style=\"width: 153px; height: 130px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f229f5f4-3801-4cd9-8739-37221893eafd-image.png\" style=\"width: 155px; height: 130px;\" /></p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Titration curve of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></math> vs&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCl</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>WB</mi></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mo>+</mo><mi>SA</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p>At the very beginning of the curve, the pH starts by falling quite quickly as the acid is added, but the curve very soon gets less steep. This is because a buffer solution is being set up composed of the excess ammonium hydroxide&nbsp;and the ammonium chloride being formed.</p><p>Notice that the equivalence point is now somewhat acidic ( a bit less than pH 5), because pure ammonium chloride isn&#39;t neutral. However, the equivalence point still falls on the steepest bit of the curve.&nbsp;That will turn out to be important in choosing a suitable indicator for the titration.</p><p>For the above titration the indicator suitable is methyl orange</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8c93728b-b46d-4d07-9e6c-d1493abba697-image.png\" style=\"width: 195px; height: 140px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30734,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$0.1$ M","$9.53 \\times 10^{-6}$ M","$8.1 \\times 10^{-8}$ M","$1.0 \\times 10^{-13}$ M"],"answer":2,"solution":"Given:<br>Weak dibasic acid $H_2A$ with $K_{a1} = 8.1 \\times 10^{-8}$ and $K_{a2} = 1.0 \\times 10^{-13}$<br>Initial concentration: $[H_2A]_0 = 0.1\\text{ M}$<br>The solution also contains $0.1\\text{ M HCl}$, which dissociates completely to give $[H^+]_0 = 0.1\\text{ M}$.<br><br>The main source of $HA^-$ is the first dissociation:<br>$H_2A \\rightleftharpoons H^+ + HA^-$<br><br>Let $x$ be the amount of $H_2A$ that dissociates. Then at equilibrium:<br>$[H_2A] = 0.1 - x$<br>$[H^+] = 0.1 + x$<br>$[HA^-] = x$<br><br>Applying the equilibrium expression:<br>$K_{a1} = \\dfrac{[H^+][HA^-]}{[H_2A]}$<br><br>$8.1 \\times 10^{-8} = \\dfrac{(0.1 + x)(x)}{0.1 - x}$<br><br>Since $K_{a1}$ is very small and the common $H^+$ ion from HCl suppresses dissociation, $x \\ll 0.1$. Hence:<br>$0.1 - x \\approx 0.1$ and $0.1 + x \\approx 0.1$<br><br>$8.1 \\times 10^{-8} \\approx \\dfrac{(0.1)(x)}{0.1} = x$<br><br>Therefore:<br>$[HA^-] = x = 8.1 \\times 10^{-8}\\text{ M}$<br><br>The second dissociation ($K_{a2} = 1.0 \\times 10^{-13}$) is negligible compared to the first, so the $HA^-$ consumed in that step is insignificant.<br><br>Hence, the correct option is $(3)\\ 8.1 \\times 10^{-8}\\text{ M}$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (02 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30839,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["1.798 L","0.36 L","17.98 L","0.18 L"],"answer":3,"solution":"<math><msub><mrow><msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>K</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>s</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msub><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>b</mi><msub><mrow><mi>C</mi><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>32</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>PbCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><msup><mi>Pb</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi></mtd><mtd><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi></mtd><mtd><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mtable><mtr><mtd><mo>+</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi></mtd><mtd><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math><br /><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>s</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>P</mi><msup><mrow><mi>b</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mi>&#160;</mi></mrow></mfenced><msup><mrow><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>C</mi><msup><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>s</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mi>&#160;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mn>32</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><br /><math><msup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mi>&#160;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><br /><math><mi>s</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mi>M</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>M</mi><mo>.</mo><mi>w</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><mn>0.1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>278</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mi>L</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0.1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>278</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0.18</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>L</mi></math>&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30767,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>When concentration of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;ion is more than&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>, the proton concentration from water must be considered. Hence, the pH of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>HCl</mi></math>&nbsp;solution is not equal to 8.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munder><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msubsup><mi>PO</mi><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup></mrow><mi>Acid</mi></munder><mover><mo>&#8652;</mo><mrow></mrow></mover><munder><msubsup><mi>HPO</mi><mn>4</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup><mrow><mi>Conjugate</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>base</mi></mrow></munder><mo>+</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">w</mi></msub></math> increase with increase in temperature as dissociation of water increases with increase in temperature.</p><p>When weak monoprotic acid is titrated against strong base, at half neutralization point, the solution becomes acidic buffer and its <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pH</mi></math> is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pH</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>pK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>log</mi><mfrac><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mi>Salt</mi></mfenced><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mi>Acid</mi></mfenced></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>pH</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>pK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mi>salt</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mi>acid</mi></mfenced></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (15 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30845,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<math><mn>6.9</mn></math>","<math><mn>7.0</mn></math>","<math><mn>1.0</mn></math>","<math><mn>7.2</mn></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"Hydrolysis of&nbsp; salt of weak acid and weak base<br /><br /><math > <mrow> <mtext>pH</mtext><mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mn>1</mn> <mn>2</mn> </mfrac> <mfenced> <mrow> <msub> <mrow> <mtext>pK</mtext></mrow> <mtext>w</mtext> </msub> <mo>+</mo><msub> <mrow> <mtext>pK</mtext></mrow> <mtext>a</mtext> </msub> <mo>−</mo><msub> <mrow> <mtext>pK</mtext></mrow> <mtext>b</mtext> </msub> </mrow> </mfenced></mrow> </math><br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>14</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>3.2</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>3.4</mn></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mn>6.9</mn></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (02 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30825,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<math><mn>2.49</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>2.49</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>1.84</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>","<math><mn>1.84</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>","<math><mn>6.23</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>11</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>1.84</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munder><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">'</mi></msup></munder><msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8652;</mo><munder><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">'</mi></msup></munder><mo>+</mo><munder><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mrow><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">'</mi></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#8771;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></munder></math><br /><math><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#39;</mi></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>1.84</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><math><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#39;</mi></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>1.84</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>11</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><math><mo>(</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#39;</mi></mrow></msup><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>2.491</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30868,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$5.0 \\times 10^{-5}$","$5.0 \\times 10^{15}$","$5.0 \\times 10^{-15}$","$0.0 \\times 10^5$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\begin{array}{ll}\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{A} \\rightleftharpoons \\mathrm{HA}^{-}+\\mathrm{H}^{+} & \\mathrm{K}_1=\\frac{\\left[\\mathrm{HA}^{-}\\right]\\left[\\mathrm{H}^{+}\\right]}{\\left[\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{A}\\right]}  \\quad \\dots (1)\\\\ \\mathrm{HA}^{-} \\rightleftharpoons \\mathrm{H}^{+}+\\mathrm{A}^{2-} & \\mathrm{K}_2=\\frac{\\left[\\mathrm{H}^{+}\\right]\\left[\\mathrm{A}^{2-}\\right]}{\\left[\\mathrm{HA}^{-}\\right]}\\quad \\dots(2)\\end{array}$\nFor the reaction\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{A} \\rightleftharpoons 2 \\mathrm{H}^{+}+\\mathrm{A}^{2-} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{K}=\\frac{\\left[\\mathrm{H}^{+}\\right]^2\\left[\\mathrm{~A}^{2-}\\right]}{\\left[\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{A}\\right]}=\\mathrm{K}_1 \\times \\mathrm{K}_2 \\\\\n& =1 \\times 10^{-5} \\times 5 \\times 10^{-10} \\\\\n& =5 \\times 10^{-15}\n\\end{aligned}$\nHence, (C) is correct.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2007","image":null},{"id":30772,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>For the insoluble salt barium sulphate, sulphate ion added is the common ion. Due to the common&nbsp;ion effect the solubility of barium sulphate decreases. Let us assume solubility of barium sulphate is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></math>.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BaSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8652;</mo><munder><msup><mi>Ba</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></munder><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><munder><msubsup><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></munder><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munder><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></munder><mo>&#10230;</mo><munder><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></munder><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><munder><msubsup><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></munder><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi>SP</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msup><mi>Ba</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mfenced><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msubsup><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup></mfenced></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8771;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>233</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mi>gL</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30805,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Most precise volume of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCl</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>ml</mi></math></p><p>at equivalence point</p><p>Meq. of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo></math>meq. of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCl</mi></math></p><p>Let molarity of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p>solution <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>,&nbsp;then</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mol</mi><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mM</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30866,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$28.3 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~g}$","$2.83 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{~g}$","$1.0 \\times 10^{-7} \\mathrm{~g}$","$1.0 \\times 10^{-4} \\mathrm{~g}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\mathrm{AgIO}_3(\\mathrm{s}) \\rightleftharpoons \\mathrm{Ag}^{+}(\\mathrm{aq})+\\mathrm{IO}_3^{-}(\\mathrm{aq})$\nLet the solubility of $\\mathrm{AgIO}_3$ be $\\mathrm{s}$\n$\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}=\\left[\\mathrm{Ag}^{+}\\right]\\left[\\mathrm{IO}_3^{-}\\right]$\n$1.0 \\times 10^{-8}=\\mathrm{s}^2$\n$\\mathrm{s}=10^{-4} \\mathrm{~mol} / \\mathrm{litre}$\n$=\\frac{10^{-4} \\times 283}{1000} \\times 100$\n$=283 \\times 10^{-5}$\n$=2.83 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{~g} / 100 \\mathrm{~ml}$\nHence, (B) is correct.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2007","image":null},{"id":30856,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$1.40 \\times 10^{-9}$","$0.14 \\times 10^{-9}$","$140 \\times 10^{-9}$","$14.0 \\times 10^{-9}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\mathrm{PbI}_2 \\leftrightharpoons \\mathrm{Pb}^{++}+2 \\mathrm{I}^{-}$\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\nK_{\\text {sp }}= & s \\times(2 s)^2=4 s^3 \\\\\n& =4 \\times\\left(\\frac{0.7}{461.2}\\right)^3=14.0 \\times 10^{-9}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (26 May Online)","image":null},{"id":30829,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"For titration of strong base with strong acid <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math> changes sharply near equivalence point and at equivalent point <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math> sharply decreases because strong base &amp; strong acid dissociate completely.<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow></mover><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mo>+</mo><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mover><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi>aCl</mi><mo>+</mo><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mfenced></math><br />at equivalent point <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn></math> and at endpoint solution will be neutral.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30857,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$1 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{M} \\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ and $1 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{M} \\mathrm{F}^{-}$","$1 \\times 10^{-4} \\mathrm{M} \\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ and $1 \\times 10^{-4} \\mathrm{M} \\mathrm{F}^{-}$","$1 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{M} \\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ and $1 \\times 10^{-5} \\mathrm{M} \\mathrm{F}^{-}$","$1 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{M} \\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ and $1 \\times 10^{-5} \\mathrm{M} \\mathrm{F}^{-}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"When ionic product i.e. the product of the concentration of ions in the solution exceeds the value of solubility product, formation of precitpiate occurs.\n$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{CaF}_2 \\rightleftharpoons \\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}+2 \\mathrm{~F}^{-} \\\\ & \\text {Ionic product }=\\left[\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}\\right]\\left[\\mathrm{F}^{-}\\right]^2 \\\\ & \\text { when, }\\left[\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}\\right]=1 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{M} \\\\ & {\\left[\\mathrm{F}^{-}\\right]^2=\\left(1 \\times 10^{-3}\\right)^2 \\mathrm{M} } \\\\ & =1 \\times 10^{-6} \\mathrm{M} \\\\ \\therefore & {\\left[\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}\\right]\\left[\\mathrm{F}^{-}\\right]^2=\\left(1 \\times 10^{-2}\\right)\\left(1 \\times 10^{-6}\\right)=1 \\times 10^{-8} } \\\\ & \\text { In this case, } \\\\ & \\text { Ionic product }\\left(1 \\times 10^{-8}\\right)> \\\\ & \\text { solubility product }\\left(1.7 \\times 10^{-10}\\right)\\end{aligned}$\n$\\therefore$ Hence (a) is correct option.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (19 May Online)","image":null},{"id":30771,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["Both <strong>Statement-I</strong> and <strong>Statement-II</strong> are incorrect","<strong>Statement-I</strong> is incorrect but <strong>Statement-II</strong> is correct","Both <strong>Statement-I</strong> and <strong>Statement-II</strong> are correct","<strong>Statement-</strong>I is correct but <strong>Statement-II </strong>is incorrect"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Methyl orange is a weak acid. Additionally, in acidic conditions, methyl orange exists in the quinonoid form, which is red in color. In alkaline conditions, it exists in the benzenoid form, which is yellow in color.&nbsp;Since red is more deeply coloured than yellow, Statement-2 is wrong.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/df1104fa-43df-4eb0-8873-6750cb3acdbd-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 216px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30787,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The solubility product constant is the equilibrium constant for the dissolution of a solid substance into an aqueous solution. It is denoted by the symbol <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi>sp</mi></msub></math>.</p><p>Solubility of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CaF</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mole</mi><mo>/</mo><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>34</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>78</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>34</mn></mrow><mn>78</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mol</mi><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi>sp</mi></msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CaF</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>108</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0108</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mfenced><mrow><mi>mol</mi><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30735,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$0.7 \\quad 2.0$","$2.0 \\quad 3.3$","$1.1 \\quad 2.2$","$3.0 \\quad 2.2$"],"answer":1,"solution":"For part (a), at the start of the titration, the solution contains only the weak acid HX.<br><br>The concentration of HX is $C = 0.2$ M.<br><br>Using the formula for the hydrogen ion concentration of a weak acid with $\\alpha \\ll 1$:<br><br>$[H^+] = \\sqrt{K_a \\times C} = \\sqrt{5 \\times 10^{-4} \\times 0.2} = \\sqrt{10^{-4}} = 10^{-2}$ M<br><br>$pH = -\\log(10^{-2}) = 2.0$<br><br>For part (b), when $10$ mL of $0.2$ M NaOH is added to $20$ mL of $0.2$ M HX:<br><br>Initial millimoles of HX $= 20 \\times 0.2 = 4$ mmol<br><br>Millimoles of NaOH added $= 10 \\times 0.2 = 2$ mmol<br><br>The added NaOH neutralizes half of the HX to form NaX, creating an acidic buffer.<br><br>Millimoles of HX remaining $= 4 - 2 = 2$ mmol<br><br>Millimoles of NaX formed $= 2$ mmol<br><br>Using the Henderson-Hasselbalch equation:<br><br>$pH = pK_a + \\log \\left( \\dfrac{[\\text{Salt}]}{[\\text{Acid}]} \\right)$<br><br>Since the millimoles of salt and acid are equal, $\\log(1) = 0$.<br><br>$pH = pK_a = 3.3$<br><br>Answer: $2.0 \\quad 3.3$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (02 April Shift 2)","image":null}]